entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 5 at 8:09PM SST by NWS Pago Pago AS
entry.summary:
Tropical Disturbance 08F (TD08F) along the active South Pacific Convergence Zone (SPCZ) is forecast to bring damaging winds, heavy rain and hazardous ocean conditions tonight through Tuesday, mainly focusing over Manu'a, Swains and Rose atoll. Latest model runs show TD08F within the SPCZ, currently located to the northwest of the territory, moving quickly to the north of Tutuila then turning southeast between Manu'a Islands and Rose atoll Tuesday.
At this time, there is a low chance of Tutuila and Aunu'u getting impacted by the above system. However, a slight shift in the SPCZ axis may quickly increase this chance. Therefore, we urge the public to continue staying prepared throughout our hurricane season (November until April) and stay informed with latest updates from the NWS WSO Pago Pago office via website: www.weather.gov/ppg or social media @NWSPagoPago. You may also listen to the NOAA weather radio or call our office at (684) 699-9130 for latest updates.

entry.summary:
A deep layered-trough and accompanying frontal boundary will promote favorable weather conditions for the development of thunderstorms, strong winds and flooding rains as early as Tuesday morning through at least early Thursday morning. Under a southerly steering wind flow, above-normal moisture will be pulled from the Southern Caribbean over Puerto Rico and the U.S Virgin Islands. This will increase the risk for urban and flash flooding, rapid river rises and mudslides everywhere.
The Flood Watch continues for
* Portions of Puerto Rico and Virgin Islands, including the following areas, in Puerto Rico, Central Interior, Culebra, Eastern Interior, Mayaguez and Vicinity, North Central, Northeast, Northwest, Ponce and Vicinity, San Juan and Vicinity, Southeast, Southwest, Vieques, and Western Interior. In Virgin Islands, St Croix and St.Thomas...St. John...and Adjacent Islands.
* From 6 AM AST Tuesday through 6 AM early Thursday morning
* WHEN...From early Tuesday morning through early Thursday morning.
* IMPACTS...Increases risk for urban and flash flooding, rapid river rises and mudslides across the area.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS... - The most likely scenario is that the higher rainfall accumulations should range between 3 and 6 inches, especially for the southern, interior and eastern sections of Puerto Rico, and between 2 and 4 inches along the U.S. Virgin Islands. Isolated higher amounts, up to 8 inches is the reasonable worst case scenario in these areas. - http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 5 at 3:39PM AKST by NWS Fairbanks AK
entry.summary:
A very strong storm will move north over the Eastern Bering Sea Tuesday through Thursday. This low is expected to bring strong southerly gales, along with snow and blowing snow to the West Coast from the Yukon Delta to the Bering Strait starting on Tuesday night and continuing into Thursday.
Winds gusting to 60 mph and periods of blizzard conditions and freezing rain or sleet are expected over the Yukon Delta and St Lawrence Island with this storm from Tuesday afternoon through Thursday. Winds gusting 40 to 50 mph and blowing snow with periods of low visibility are expected Tuesday evening into Thursday for inland sections of the Yukon Delta, along the Norton Sound Coast, and in the Bering Strait.
Southerly gales developing Tuesday night over the Eastern Bering Sea will continue through Wednesday night. This will bring water levels up 2 to 3 feet from the Bering Strait south Wednesday through Thursday, which could cause water to seep up onto the ice along the coast on Wednesday into Thu. No flooding is expected, but this could affect the trails that cross ice near the coast from the Bering Strait south.
A weaker storm moving north over the West Coast tonight will bring briefly reduced visibility in blowing snow and winds gusting 25 to 40 mph tonight. Those winds will decrease slightly on Tuesday morning before the strong storm mentioned above moves north Tuesday afternoon and evening.

entry.title: Avalanche Warning issued February 5 at 6:37AM PST by NWS Las Vegas NV
entry.summary:
AVWVEF
The Eastern Sierra Avalanche Center in Mammoth Lakes has continued a Backcountry Avalanche Warning for the following areas: the Eastern Sierra in Mono County and the Eastern Sierra in Inyo County
* WHAT...Avalanche Danger remains at HIGH at all elevations this morning. Very dangerous avalanche conditions are expected through noon, Monday, February 5, 2024.
* WHERE...The eastern slopes of the Sierra Nevada mountain range between Virginia Lakes to the north to Bishop Creek to the south.
* WHEN...In effect from Mon 07:00 PST to Mon 12:00 PST..
* IMPACTS...Intense snowfall and strong winds have overloaded the snowpack, which contains buried persistent weak layers. Backcountry travel will be difficult and dangerous. Expect widespread areas of unstable snow.
* PRECAUTIONARY / PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...Very dangerous avalanche conditions. Travel in avalanche terrain is not recommended. Avalanche danger is expected to begin decreasing on Monday afternoon. Visit esavlanche.org for more information.
Consult http://www.esavalanche.org or www.avalanche.org for more detailed information
Similar avalanche danger may exist at locations outside the coverage area of this or any avalanche center.
entry.cap:areaDesc: Eastern Sierra Slopes of Inyo County

entry.summary:

The Sierra Avalanche Center in Truckee has continued a BACKCOUNTRY AVALANCHE WARNING for the following areas: NWS Reno NV - NVZ002 (Greater Lake Tahoe)...CAZ072 (Greater Lake Tahoe (CA))
* WHAT...Avalanche danger is expected to remain at HIGH avalanche danger in the backcountry through Tuesday.
* WHERE...Central Sierra Nevada Mountains between Yuba Pass (Hwy 49) on the north and Ebbetts Pass (Hwy 4) on the south, including the greater Lake Tahoe area. This does not include ski areas and highways where avalanche mitigation programs exist.
* WHEN...In effect from Sun 06:57 PST to Tue 07:00 PST.

entry.title: Avalanche Warning issued February 5 at 5:41AM MST by NWS Great Falls MT
entry.summary:
AVWTFX
THE FOLLOWING MESSAGE IS TRANSMITTED AT THE REQUEST OF THE GALLATIN NATIONAL FOREST AVALANCHE CENTER.
ISSUED ON February 05 2024 AT 05:35 am
AVALANCHE WARNING
The Gallatin National Forest Avalanche Center is continuing a Backcountry Avalanche Warning for the Centennial Mountains in Island Park, the Lionhead area near West Yellowstone, and the southern Madison and southern Gallatin ranges. New snow and wind are forming drifts and overloading an exceptionally weak snowpack, creating very dangerous avalanche conditions. Human- triggered and natural avalanches are likely. Avoid avalanche terrain and avalanche runout zones. The avalanche danger is HIGH on all slopes. Contact the Gallatin National Forest Avalanche Center for more detailed information. This warning will expire or be updated by 6:00 a.m. on Tuesday February 6.
entry.cap:areaDesc: Gallatin and Madison County Mountains and Centennial Mountains
